# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pcie-interface
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Attached devices can take either the form of an integrated circuit fitted onto the motherboard (called a *planar device* in the PCI specification) or an expansion card that fits into a slot.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The PCI Local Bus was first implemented in IBM PC compatibles, where it displaced the combination of several slow Industry Standard Architecture (ISA) slots and one fast VESA Local Bus (VLB) slot as the bus configuration.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] It has subsequently been adopted for other computer types.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Typical PCI cards used in PCs include: network cards, sound cards, modems, extra ports such as Universal Serial Bus (USB) or serial, TV tuner cards and hard disk drive host adapters.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] PCI video cards replaced ISA and VLB cards until rising bandwidth needs outgrew the abilities of PCI.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The preferred interface for video cards then became Accelerated Graphics Port (AGP), a superset of PCI, before giving way to PCI Express.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The first PCI specification was developed by Intel, but subsequent development of the standard became the responsibility of the *PCI Special Interest Group* (PCI-SIG).
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The first version of PCI found in retail desktop computers was a 32-bit bus using a 33 MHz bus clock and 5 V signaling, although the PCI 1.0 standard provided for a 64-bit variant as well.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] These have one locating notch in the card.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Version 2.0 of the PCI standard introduced 3.3 V slots, physically distinguished by a flipped physical connector to prevent accidental insertion of 5 V cards.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Universal cards, which can operate on either voltage, have two notches.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Version 2.1 of the PCI standard introduced optional 66 MHz operation.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] A server-oriented variant of PCI, PCI Extended (PCI-X) operated at frequencies up to 133 MHz for PCI-X 1.0 and up to 533 MHz for PCI-X 2.0.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] An internal connector for laptop cards, called **Mini PCI**, was introduced in version 2.2 of the PCI specification.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The PCI bus was also adopted as an external laptop connector standard – CardBus.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] PCI and PCI-X are sometimes referred to as either **Parallel PCI** or **Conventional PCI** to distinguish them technologically from their more recent successor PCI Express, which adopted a serial, lane-based architecture.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] PCI's heyday in the desktop computer market was approximately 1995 to 2005.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] PCI and PCI-X have become obsolete for most purposes and have largely disappeared from many other modern motherboards since 2013; however they are still common on some modern desktops as of 2020 for the purposes of backward compatibility and the relative low cost to produce.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Another common modern application of parallel PCI is in industrial PCs, where many specialized expansion cards, used here, never transitioned to PCI Express, just as some ISA cards never transitioned to PCI.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Many kinds of devices formerly available on PCI expansion cards are now commonly integrated onto motherboards or available in USB and PCI Express versions.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Work on PCI began at the Intel Architecture Labs (IAL, also Architecture Development Lab) c.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] A team of primarily IAL engineers defined the architecture and developed a proof of concept chipset and platform (Saturn) partnering with teams in the company's desktop PC systems and core logic product organizations.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] PCI was immediately put to use in servers, replacing Micro Channel architecture (MCA) and Extended Industry Standard Architecture (EISA) as the server expansion bus of choice.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] In mainstream PCs, PCI was slower to replace VLB, and did not gain significant market penetration until late 1994 in second-generation Pentium PCs.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] By 1996, VLB was all but extinct, and manufacturers had adopted PCI even for Intel 80486 (486) computers.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] EISA continued to be used alongside PCI through 2000.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Apple Computer adopted PCI for professional Power Macintosh computers (replacing NuBus) in mid-1995, and the consumer Performa product line (replacing LC Processor Direct Slot (PDS)) in mid-1996.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Outside the server market, the 64-bit version of plain PCI remained rare in practice though, although it was used for example by all (post-iMac) G3 and G4 Power Macintosh computers.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Later revisions of PCI added new features and performance improvements, including a 66 MHz 3.3 V standard and 133 MHz PCI-X, and the adaptation of PCI signaling to other form factors.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Both PCI-X 1.0b and PCI-X 2.0 are backward compatible with some PCI standards.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] These revisions were used on server hardware but consumer PC hardware remained nearly all 32-bit, 33 MHz and 5 volt.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The PCI-SIG introduced the serial PCI Express in c.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Since then, motherboard manufacturers gradually included fewer or zero PCI slots in favor of the new standard.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Bridge adapters allow the use of legacy PCI cards with PCI Express motherboards.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] PCI provides separate memory and memory-mapped I/O port address spaces for the x86 processor family, 64 and 32 bits, respectively.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Addresses in these address spaces are assigned by software.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] A third address space, called the PCI Configuration Space, which uses a fixed addressing scheme, allows software to determine the amount of memory and I/O address space needed by each device.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Each device can request up to six areas of memory space or input/output (I/O) port space via its configuration space registers.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] In a typical system, the firmware (or operating system) queries all PCI buses at startup time (via PCI Configuration Space) to find out what devices are present and what system resources (memory space, I/O space, interrupt lines, etc.) each needs.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] It then allocates the resources and tells each device what its allocation is.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The PCI configuration space also contains a small amount of device type information, which helps an operating system choose device drivers for it, or at least to have a dialogue with a user about the system configuration.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Devices may have an on-board read-only memory (ROM) containing executable code for x86 or PA-RISC processors, an Open Firmware driver, or an Option ROM.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] These are typically needed for devices used during system startup, before device drivers are loaded by the operating system.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] In addition, there are *PCI Latency Timers* that are a mechanism for *PCI Bus-Mastering* devices to share the PCI bus fairly.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] "Fair" in this case means that devices will not use such a large portion of the available PCI bus bandwidth that other devices are not able to get needed work done.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Note, this does not apply to PCI Express.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Devices are required to follow a protocol so that the interrupt-request (IRQ) lines can be shared.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The PCI bus includes four interrupt lines, INTA# through INTD#, all of which are available to each device.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Up to eight PCI devices share the same IRQ line (INTINA# through INTINH#) in APIC-enabled x86 systems.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Interrupt lines are not wired in parallel as are the other PCI bus lines.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The positions of the interrupt lines rotate between slots, so what appears to one device as the INTA# line is INTB# to the next and INTC# to the one after that.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Single-function devices usually use their INTA# for interrupt signaling, so the device load is spread fairly evenly across the four available interrupt lines.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] This alleviates a common problem with sharing interrupts.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The mapping of PCI interrupt lines onto system interrupt lines, through the PCI host bridge, is implementation-dependent.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Platform-specific firmware or operating system code is meant to know this, and set the "interrupt line" field in each device's configuration space indicating which IRQ it is connected to.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] PCI interrupt lines are level-triggered.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] This was chosen over edge-triggering to gain an advantage when servicing a shared interrupt line, and for robustness: edge-triggered interrupts are easy to miss.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Later revisions of the PCI specification add support for message-signaled interrupts.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] In this system, a device signals its need for service by performing a memory write, rather than by asserting a dedicated line.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] This alleviates the problem of scarcity of interrupt lines.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Even if interrupt vectors are still shared, it does not suffer the sharing problems of level-triggered interrupts.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] It also resolves the routing problem, because the memory write is not unpredictably modified between device and host.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Finally, because the message signaling is in-band, it resolves some synchronization problems that can occur with posted writes and out-of-band interrupt lines.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] PCI Express does not have physical interrupt lines at all.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] It uses message-signaled interrupts exclusively.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The PCI specification also provides options for 3.3 V signaling, 64-bit bus width, and 66 MHz clocking, but these are not commonly encountered outside of PCI-X support on server motherboards.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The PCI bus arbiter performs bus arbitration among multiple masters on the PCI bus.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Any number of bus masters can reside on the PCI bus, as well as requests for the bus.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] One pair of request and grant signals is dedicated to each bus master.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Typical PCI cards have either one or two key notches, depending on their signaling voltage.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Cards requiring 3.3 volts have a notch 56.21 mm from the card backplate in pin positions 12 and 13; those requiring 5 volts have a notch 104.41 mm from the backplate in pin positions 50 and 51.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] This allows cards to be fitted only into slots with a voltage they support.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] "Universal cards" accepting either voltage have both key notches.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The PCI connector is defined as having 62 contacts on each side of the edge connector, but two or four of them are replaced by key notches, so a card has 60 or 58 contacts on each side.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Side A refers to the 'solder side' and side B refers to the 'component side': if the card is held with the connector pointing down, a view of side A will have the backplate on the right, whereas a view of side B will have the backplate on the left.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The pinout of B and A sides are as follows, looking down into the motherboard connector (pins A1 and B1 are closest to backplate).
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] 64-bit PCI extends this by an additional 32 contacts on each side which provide AD[63:32], C/BE[7:4]#, the PAR64 parity signal, and a number of power and ground pins.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Most lines are connected to each slot in parallel.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Most 32-bit PCI cards will function properly in 64-bit PCI-X slots, but the bus clock rate will be limited to the clock frequency of the slowest card, an inherent limitation of PCI's shared bus topology.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] For example, when a PCI 2.3, 66-MHz peripheral is installed into a PCI-X bus capable of 133 MHz, the entire bus backplane will be limited to 66 MHz.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] To get around this limitation, many motherboards have two or more PCI/PCI-X buses, with one bus intended for use with high-speed PCI-X peripherals, and the other bus intended for general-purpose peripherals.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Many 64-bit PCI-X cards are designed to work in 32-bit mode if inserted in shorter 32-bit connectors, with some loss of performance.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] An example of this is the Adaptec 29160 64-bit SCSI interface card.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] However, some 64-bit PCI-X cards do not work in standard 32-bit PCI slots.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Installing a 64-bit PCI-X card in a 32-bit slot will leave the 64-bit portion of the card edge connector not connected and overhanging.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] This requires that there be no motherboard components positioned so as to mechanically obstruct the overhanging portion of the card edge connector.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Many Mini PCI devices were developed such as Wi-Fi, Fast Ethernet, Bluetooth, modems (often Winmodems), sound cards, cryptographic accelerators, SCSI, IDE–ATA, SATA controllers and combination cards.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Mini PCI cards can be used with regular PCI-equipped hardware, using Mini PCI-to-PCI *converters*.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Mini PCI has been superseded by the much narrower PCI Express Mini Card.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Mini PCI cards have a 2 W maximum power consumption, which limits the functionality that can be implemented in this form factor.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] They also are required to support the CLKRUN# PCI signal used to start and stop the PCI clock for power management purposes.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] There are three card form factors: Type I, Type II, and Type III cards.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The card connector used for each type include: Type I and II use a 100-pin stacking connector, while Type III uses a 124-pin edge connector, i.e. the connector for Types I and II differs from that for Type III, where the connector is on the edge of a card, like with a SO-DIMM.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The additional 24 pins provide the extra signals required to route I/O back through the system connector (audio, AC-Link, LAN, phone-line interface).
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Type II cards have RJ11 and RJ45 mounted connectors.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] These cards must be located at the edge of the computer or docking station so that the RJ11 and RJ45 ports can be mounted for external access.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Mini PCI is distinct from 144-pin Micro PCI.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] PCI bus traffic consists of a series of PCI bus transactions.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Each transaction consists of an *address phase* followed by one or more *data phases*.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The direction of the data phases may be from initiator to target (write transaction) or vice versa (read transaction), but all of the data phases must be in the same direction.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Either party may pause or halt the data phases at any point.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Any PCI device may initiate a transaction.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] First, it must request permission from a PCI bus arbiter on the motherboard.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The arbiter grants permission to one of the requesting devices.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The initiator begins the address phase by broadcasting a 32-bit address plus a 4-bit command code, then waits for a target to respond.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] All other devices examine this address and one of them responds a few cycles later.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] 64-bit addressing is done using a two-stage address phase.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The initiator broadcasts the low 32 address bits, accompanied by a special "dual address cycle" command code.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Devices that do not support 64-bit addressing can simply not respond to that command code.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The next cycle, the initiator transmits the high 32 address bits, plus the real command code.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The transaction operates identically from that point on.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] To ensure compatibility with 32-bit PCI devices, it is forbidden to use a dual address cycle if not necessary, i.e. if the high-order address bits are all zero.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] While the PCI bus transfers 32 bits per data phase, the initiator transmits 4 active-low byte enable signals indicating which 8-bit bytes are to be considered significant.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] In particular, a write must affect only the enabled bytes in the target PCI device.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] They are of little importance for memory reads, but I/O reads might have side effects.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The PCI standard explicitly allows a data phase with no bytes enabled, which must behave as a no-op.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] PCI has three address spaces: memory, I/O address, and configuration.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Memory addresses are 32 bits (optionally 64 bits) in size, support caching and can be burst transactions.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] I/O addresses are for compatibility with the Intel x86 architecture's I/O port address space.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Although the PCI bus specification allows burst transactions in any address space, most devices only support it for memory addresses and not I/O.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Finally, PCI configuration space provides access to 256 bytes of special configuration registers per PCI device.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Each PCI slot gets its own configuration space address range.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The registers are used to configure devices memory and I/O address ranges they should respond to from transaction initiators.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] When a computer is first turned on, all PCI devices respond only to their configuration space accesses.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The computer's BIOS scans for devices and assigns Memory and I/O address ranges to them.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] If an address is not claimed by any device, the transaction initiator's address phase will time out causing the initiator to abort the operation.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] In case of reads, it is customary to supply all-ones for the read data value (0xFFFFFFFF) in this case.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] PCI devices therefore generally attempt to avoid using the all-ones value in important status registers, so that such an error can be easily detected by software.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] There are 16 possible 4-bit command codes, and 12 of them are assigned.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] With the exception of the unique dual address cycle, the least significant bit of the command code indicates whether the following data phases are a read (data sent from target to initiator) or a write (data sent from an initiator to target).
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] PCI targets must examine the command code as well as the address and not respond to address phases that specify an unsupported command code.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The commands that refer to cache lines depend on the PCI configuration space cache line size register being set up properly; they may not be used until that has been done.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] This is a special form of read cycle implicitly addressed to the interrupt controller, which returns an interrupt vector.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] One possible implementation is to generate an interrupt acknowledge cycle on an ISA bus using a PCI/ISA bus bridge.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] style interrupt controller on the PCI bus, this cycle need never be used.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] This cycle is a special broadcast write of system events that PCI card may be interested in.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The address field of a special cycle is ignored, but it is followed by a data phase containing a payload message.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The currently defined messages announce that the processor is stopping for some reason (e.g. to save power).
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] No device ever responds to this cycle; it is always terminated with a master abort after leaving the data on the bus for at least 4 cycles.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] All 32 bits of the read address are provided, so that a device may (for compatibility reasons) implement less than 4 bytes worth of I/O registers.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] If the byte enables request data not within the address range supported by the PCI device (e.g. a 4-byte read from a device which only supports 2 bytes of I/O address space), it must be terminated with a target abort.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Multiple data cycles are permitted, using linear (simple incrementing) burst ordering.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The PCI standard is discouraging the use of I/O space in new devices, preferring that as much as possible be done through main memory mapping.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] A PCI device must not respond to an address cycle with these command codes.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] This performs a read cycle from memory space.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] the two least significant bits of the address are not needed during the address phase; equivalent information will arrive during the data phases in the form of byte select signals.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] They instead specify the order in which burst data must be returned.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] If a device does not support the requested order, it must provide the first word and then disconnect.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] If a memory space is marked as "prefetchable", then the target device must ignore the byte-select signals on a memory read and always return 32 valid bits.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] This operates similarly to a memory read.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The byte select signals are more important in a write, as unselected bytes must not be written to memory.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Generally, PCI writes are faster than PCI reads, because a device may buffer the incoming write data and release the bus faster.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] For a read, it must delay the data phase until the data has been fetched.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] This is similar to an I/O read, but reads from PCI configuration space.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] A device must respond only if the low 11 bits of the address specify a function and register that it implements, and if the special IDSEL signal is asserted.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Burst reads (using linear incrementing) are permitted in PCI configuration space.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Unlike I/O space, standard PCI configuration registers are defined so that reads never disturb the state of the device.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] It is possible for a device to have configuration space registers beyond the standard 64 bytes which have read side effects, but this is rare.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Configuration space accesses often have a few cycles of delay to allow the IDSEL lines to stabilize, which makes them slower than other forms of access.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Also, a configuration space access requires a multi-step operation rather than a single machine instruction.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Thus, it is best to avoid them during routine operation of a PCI device.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] This operates analogously to a configuration read.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] A target is always permitted to consider this a synonym for a generic memory read.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] When accessing a memory address that requires more than 32 bits to represent, the address phase begins with this command and the low 32 bits of the address, followed by a second cycle with the actual command and the high 32 bits of the address.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] PCI targets that do not support 64-bit addressing may simply treat this as another reserved command code and not respond to it.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] This command code may only be used with a non-zero high-order address word; it is forbidden to use this cycle if not necessary.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] This command is identical to a generic memory read, but includes the hint that the read will continue to the end of the cache line.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] This command is identical to a generic memory write, but comes with the guarantee that one or more whole cache lines will be written, with all byte selects enabled.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] This is an optimization for write-back caches snooping the bus.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Normally, a write-back cache holding dirty data must interrupt the write operation long enough to write its own dirty data first.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] If the write is performed using this command, the data to be written back is guaranteed to be irrelevant, and may simply be invalidated in the write-back cache.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] This optimization only affects the snooping cache, and makes no difference to the target, which may treat this as a synonym for the memory write command.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Soon after promulgation of the PCI specification, it was discovered that lengthy transactions by some devices, due to slow acknowledgments, long data bursts, or some combination, could cause buffer underrun or overrun in other devices.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Additionally, as of revision 2.1, all initiators capable of bursting more than two data phases must implement a programmable latency timer.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The timer starts counting clock cycles when a transaction starts (initiator asserts FRAME#).
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] If the timer has expired *and* the arbiter has removed GNT#, then the initiator must terminate the transaction at the next legal opportunity.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] This is usually the next data phase, but Memory Write and Invalidate transactions must continue to the end of the cache line.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Devices unable to meet those timing restrictions must use a combination of posted writes (for memory writes) and delayed transactions (for other writes and all reads).
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] In a delayed transaction, the target records the transaction (including the write data) internally and aborts (asserts STOP# rather than TRDY#) the first data phase.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The initiator *must* retry exactly the same transaction later.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] In the interim, the target internally performs the transaction, and waits for the retried transaction.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] When the retried transaction is seen, the buffered result is delivered.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] A device may be the target of other transactions while completing one delayed transaction; it must remember the transaction type, address, byte selects and (if a write) data value, and only complete the correct transaction.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] If the target has a limit on the number of delayed transactions that it can record internally (simple targets may impose a limit of 1), it will force those transactions to retry without recording them.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] They will be dealt with when the current delayed transaction is completed.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] If two initiators attempt the same transaction, a delayed transaction begun by one may have its result delivered to the other; this is harmless.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] A target abandons a delayed transaction when a retry succeeds in delivering the buffered result, the bus is reset, or when 215=32768 clock cycles (approximately 1 ms) elapse without seeing a retry.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The latter should never happen in normal operation, but it prevents a deadlock of the whole bus if one initiator is reset or malfunctions.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The PCI standard permits multiple independent PCI buses to be connected by bus bridges that will forward operations on one bus to another when required.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Although PCI tends not to use many bus bridges, PCI Express systems use many PCI-to-PCI bridge usually called *PCI Express Root Port*; each PCI Express slot appears to be a separate bus, connected by a bridge to the others.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The PCI host bridge (usually northbridge in x86 platforms) interconnect between CPU, main memory and PCI bus.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Generally, when a bus bridge sees a transaction on one bus that must be forwarded to the other, the original transaction must wait until the forwarded transaction completes before a result is ready.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] One notable exception occurs in the case of memory writes.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Here, the bridge may record the write data internally (if it has room) and signal completion of the write before the forwarded write has completed.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Such "sent but not yet arrived" writes are referred to as "posted writes", by analogy with a postal mail message.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Although they offer great opportunity for performance gains, the rules governing what is permissible are somewhat intricate.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] The PCI standard permits bus bridges to convert multiple bus transactions into one larger transaction under certain situations.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] This can improve the efficiency of the PCI bus.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Write transactions to consecutive addresses may be combined into a longer burst write, as long as the order of the accesses in the burst is the same as the order of the original writes.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] It is permissible to insert extra data phases with all byte enables turned off if the writes are almost consecutive.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Multiple writes to disjoint portions of the same word may be merged into a single write with multiple byte enables asserted.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] In this case, writes that were presented to the bus bridge in a particular order are merged so they occur at the same time when forwarded.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] Multiple writes to the same byte or bytes may *not* be combined, for example, by performing only the second write and skipping the first write that was overwritten.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p01] This is because the PCI specification permits writes to have side effects.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] PCI bus transactions are controlled by five main control signals, two driven by the initiator of a transaction (FRAME# and IRDY#), and three driven by the target (DEVSEL#, TRDY#, and STOP#).
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] There are two additional arbitration signals (REQ# and GNT#) that are used to obtain permission to initiate a transaction.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] All are active-low, meaning that the active or *asserted* state is a low voltage.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Pull-up resistors on the motherboard ensure they will remain high (inactive or *deasserted*) if not driven by any device, but the PCI bus does not depend on the resistors to *change* the signal level; all devices drive the signals high for one cycle before ceasing to drive the signals.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] All PCI bus signals are sampled on the rising edge of the clock.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Signals nominally change on the falling edge of the clock, giving each PCI device approximately one half a clock cycle to decide how to respond to the signals it observed on the rising edge, and one half a clock cycle to transmit its response to the other device.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The PCI bus requires that every time the device driving a PCI bus signal changes, one *turnaround cycle* must elapse between the time the one device stops driving the signal and the other device starts.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Without this, there might be a period when both devices were driving the signal, which would interfere with bus operation.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The combination of this turnaround cycle and the requirement to drive a control line high for one cycle before ceasing to drive it means that each of the main control lines must be high for a minimum of two cycles when changing owners.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The PCI bus protocol is designed so this is rarely a limitation; only in a few special cases (notably fast back-to-back transactions) is it necessary to insert additional delay to meet this requirement.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Any device on a PCI bus that is capable of acting as a bus master may initiate a transaction with any other device.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] To ensure that only one transaction is initiated at a time, each master must first wait for a bus grant signal, GNT#, from an arbiter located on the motherboard.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Each device has a separate request line REQ# that requests the bus, but the arbiter may "park" the bus grant signal at any device if there are no current requests.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The arbiter may remove GNT# at any time.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] A device that loses GNT# may complete its current transaction, but may not start one (by asserting FRAME#) unless it observes GNT# asserted the cycle before it begins.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The arbiter may also provide GNT# at any time, including during another master's transaction.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] During a transaction, either FRAME# or IRDY# or both are asserted; when both are deasserted, the bus is idle.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] A device may initiate a transaction at any time that GNT# is asserted and the bus is idle.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] A PCI bus transaction begins with an *address phase*.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The initiator (usually a chipset), seeing that it has GNT# and the bus is idle, drives the target address onto the AD[31:0] lines, the associated command (e.g. memory read, or I/O write) on the C/BE[3:0]# lines, and pulls FRAME# low.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Each other device examines the address and command and decides whether to respond as the target by asserting DEVSEL#.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] A device must respond by asserting DEVSEL# within 3 cycles.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Devices that promise to respond within 1 or 2 cycles are said to have "fast DEVSEL" or "medium DEVSEL", respectively.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] A device must latch the address on the first cycle; the initiator is required to remove the address and command from the bus on the following cycle, even before receiving a DEVSEL# response.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The additional time is available only for interpreting the address and command after it is captured.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] On the fifth cycle of the address phase (or earlier if all other devices have medium DEVSEL or faster), a catch-all "subtractive decoding" is allowed for some address ranges.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] This is commonly used by an ISA bus bridge for addresses within its range (24 bits for memory and 16 bits for I/O).
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] On the sixth cycle, if there has been no response, the initiator may abort the transaction by deasserting FRAME#.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] This is known as *master abort termination* and it is customary for PCI bus bridges to return all-ones data (0xFFFFFFFF) in this case.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] PCI devices, therefore, are generally designed to avoid using the all-ones value in important status registers, so that such an error can be easily detected by software.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] On the rising edge of clock 0, the initiator observes FRAME# and IRDY# both high, and GNT# low, so it drives the address, command, and asserts FRAME# in time for the rising edge of clock 1.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Targets latch the address and begin decoding it.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] They may respond with DEVSEL# in time for clock 2 (fast DEVSEL), 3 (medium) or 4 (slow).
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Subtractive decode devices, seeing no other response by clock 4, may respond on clock 5.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] If the master does not see a response by clock 5, it will terminate the transaction and remove FRAME# on clock 6.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] TRDY# and STOP# are deasserted (high) during the address phase.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The initiator may assert IRDY# as soon as it is ready to transfer data, which could theoretically be as soon as clock 2.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] To allow 64-bit addressing, a master will present the address over two consecutive cycles.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] First, it sends the low-order address bits with a special "dual-cycle address" command on the C/BE[3:0]#.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] On the following cycle, it sends the high-order address bits and the actual command.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Dual-address cycles are forbidden if the high-order address bits are zero, so devices that do not support 64-bit addressing can simply not respond to dual-cycle commands.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Addresses for PCI configuration space access use special decoding.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] For these, the low-order address lines specify the offset of the desired PCI configuration register, and the high-order address lines are ignored.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Instead, an additional address signal, the IDSEL input, must be high before a device may assert DEVSEL#.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Each slot connects a different high-order address line to the IDSEL pin and is selected using one-hot encoding on the upper address lines.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] After the address phase (specifically, beginning with the cycle that DEVSEL# goes low) comes a burst of one or more *data phases*.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] In all cases, the initiator drives active-low byte select signals on the C/BE[3:0]# lines, but the data on the AD[31:0] may be driven by the initiator (in case of writes) or target (in case of reads).
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] During data phases, the C/BE[3:0]# lines are interpreted as active-low *byte enables*.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] In case of a write, the asserted signals indicate which of the four bytes on the AD bus are to be written to the addressed location.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] In the case of a read, they indicate which bytes the initiator is interested in.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] For reads, it is always legal to ignore the byte-enable signals and simply return all 32 bits; cacheable memory resources are required to always return 32 valid bits.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The byte enables are mainly useful for I/O space accesses where reads have side effects.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] A data phase with all four C/BE# lines deasserted is explicitly permitted by the PCI standard, and must have no effect on the target other than to advance the address in the burst access in progress.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The data phase continues until both parties are ready to complete the transfer and continue to the next data phase.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The initiator asserts IRDY# (*initiator ready*) when it no longer needs to wait, while the target asserts TRDY# (*target ready*).
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Whichever side is providing the data must drive it on the AD bus before asserting its ready signal.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Once one of the participants asserts its ready signal, it may not become un-ready or otherwise alter its control signals until the end of the data phase.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The data recipient must latch the AD bus each cycle until it sees both IRDY# and TRDY# asserted, which marks the end of the current data phase and indicates that the just-latched data is the word to be transferred.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] To maintain full burst speed, the data sender then has half a clock cycle after seeing both IRDY# and TRDY# asserted to drive the next word onto the AD bus.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] This continues the address cycle illustrated above, assuming a single address cycle with medium DEVSEL, so the target responds in time for clock 3.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] However, at that time, neither side is ready to transfer data.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] For clock 4, the initiator is ready, but the target is not.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] On clock 5, both are ready, and a data transfer takes place (as indicated by the vertical lines).
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] For clock 6, the target is ready to transfer, but the initiator is not.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] On clock 7, the initiator becomes ready, and data is transferred.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] For clocks 8 and 9, both sides remain ready to transfer data, and data is transferred at the maximum possible rate (32 bits per clock cycle).
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] In case of a read, clock 2 is reserved for turning around the AD bus, so the target is not permitted to drive data on the bus even if it is capable of fast DEVSEL.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] A target that supports fast DEVSEL could in theory begin responding to a read on the cycle after the address is presented.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] This cycle is, however, reserved for AD bus turnaround.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Thus, a target may not drive the AD bus (and thus may not assert TRDY#) on the second cycle of a transaction.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Most targets will not be this fast and will not need any special logic to enforce this condition.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Either side may request that a burst end after the current data phase.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Simple PCI devices that do not support multi-word bursts will always request this immediately.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Even devices that do support bursts will have some limit on the maximum length they can support, such as the end of their addressable memory.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The initiator can mark any data phase as the final one in a transaction by deasserting FRAME# at the same time as it asserts IRDY#.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The cycle after the target asserts TRDY#, the final data transfer is complete, both sides deassert their respective RDY# signals, and the bus is idle again.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The master may not deassert FRAME# before asserting IRDY#, nor may it deassert FRAME# while waiting, with IRDY# asserted, for the target to assert TRDY#.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The only minor exception is a *master abort termination*, when no target responds with DEVSEL#.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Obviously, it is pointless to wait for TRDY# in such a case.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] However, even in this case, the master must assert IRDY# for at least one cycle after deasserting FRAME#.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] (Commonly, a master will assert IRDY# before receiving DEVSEL#, so it must simply hold IRDY# asserted for one cycle longer.) This is to ensure that bus turnaround timing rules are obeyed on the FRAME# line.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The target requests the initiator end a burst by asserting STOP#.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The initiator will then end the transaction by deasserting FRAME# at the next legal opportunity; if it wishes to transfer more data, it will continue in a separate transaction.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] If the target asserts STOP# and TRDY# at the same time, this indicates that the target wishes this to be the last data phase.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] For example, a target that does not support burst transfers will always do this to force single-word PCI transactions.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] This is the most efficient way for a target to end a burst.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] If the target asserts STOP# without asserting TRDY#, this indicates that the target wishes to stop without transferring data.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] STOP# is considered equivalent to TRDY# for the purpose of ending a data phase, but no data is transferred.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] , and unlike other PCI transactions, PCI initiators are required to pause slightly before continuing the operation.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Normally, a target holds DEVSEL# asserted through the last data phase.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] A target may not deassert DEVSEL# while waiting with TRDY# or STOP# low; it must do this at the beginning of a data phase.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] It will always take at least one cycle for the initiator to notice a target-initiated disconnection request and respond by deasserting FRAME#.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] If the initiator observes STOP# before asserting its own IRDY#, then it can end the burst by deasserting FRAME# at the same time as it asserts IRDY#, ending the burst after the current data phase.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] If the initiator has already asserted IRDY# (without deasserting FRAME#) by the time it observes the target's STOP#, it is committed to an additional data phase.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The target must wait through an additional data phase without data, holding STOP# asserted without TRDY#, before the transaction can end.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] If the initiator ends the burst at the same time as the target requests disconnection, there is no additional bus cycle.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] For memory space accesses, the words in a burst may be accessed in several orders.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The unnecessary low-order address bits AD[1:0] are used to convey the initiator's requested order.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] A target which does not support a particular order must terminate the burst after the first word.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Some of these orders depend on the cache line size, which is configurable on all PCI devices.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] If the starting offset within the cache line is zero, all of these modes reduce to the same order.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Cache line toggle and cache line wrap modes are two forms of critical-word-first cache line fetching.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Toggle mode XORs the supplied address with an incrementing counter.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] This is the native order for Intel 486 and Pentium processors.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] It has the advantage that it is not necessary to know the cache line size to implement it.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] PCI version 2.1 obsoleted toggle mode and added the cache line wrap mode, where fetching proceeds linearly, wrapping around at the end of each cache line.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] When one cache line is completely fetched, fetching jumps to the starting offset in the next cache line.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Most PCI devices only support a limited range of typical cache line sizes; if the cache line size is programmed to an unexpected value, they force single-word access.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] PCI also supports burst access to I/O and configuration space, but only linear mode is supported.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] On clock edge 1, the initiator starts a transaction by driving an address, command, and asserting FRAME# The other signals are idle (indicated by ^^^), pulled high by the motherboard's pull-up resistors.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] On cycle 2, the target asserts both DEVSEL# and TRDY#.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] As the initiator is also ready, a data transfer occurs.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] This repeats for three more cycles, but before the last one (clock edge 5), the master deasserts FRAME#, indicating that this is the end.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] On clock edge 6, the AD bus and FRAME# are undriven (turnaround cycle) and the other control lines are driven high for 1 cycle.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] On clock edge 7, another initiator can start a different transaction.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] This is also the turnaround cycle for the other control lines.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] On clock edge 6, the target indicates that it wants to stop (with data), but the initiator is already holding IRDY# low, so there is a fifth data phase (clock edge 7), during which no data is transferred.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The PCI bus detects parity errors, but does not attempt to correct them by retrying operations; it is purely a failure indication.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Due to this, there is no need to detect the parity error before it has happened, and the PCI bus actually detects it a few cycles later.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] During a data phase, whichever device is driving the AD[31:0] lines computes even parity over them and the C/BE[3:0]# lines, and sends that out the PAR line one cycle later.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] All access rules and turnaround cycles for the AD bus apply to the PAR line, just one cycle later.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The device listening on the AD bus checks the received parity and asserts the PERR# (parity error) line one cycle after that.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] This generally generates a processor interrupt, and the processor can search the PCI bus for the device which detected the error.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The PERR# line is only used during data phases, once a target has been selected.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] If a parity error is detected during an address phase (or the data phase of a Special Cycle), the devices which observe it assert the SERR# (System error) line.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Even when some bytes are masked by the C/BE# lines and not in use, they must still have *some* defined value, and this value must be used to compute the parity.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Due to the need for a turnaround cycle between different devices driving PCI bus signals, in general it is necessary to have an idle cycle between PCI bus transactions.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] However, in some circumstances it is permitted to skip this idle cycle, going directly from the final cycle of one transfer (IRDY# asserted, FRAME# deasserted) to the first cycle of the next (FRAME# asserted, IRDY# deasserted).
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Additional timing constraints may come from the need to turn around are the target control lines, particularly DEVSEL#.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The target deasserts DEVSEL#, driving it high, in the cycle following the final data phase, which in the case of back-to-back transactions is the first cycle of the address phase.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The second cycle of the address phase is then reserved for DEVSEL# turnaround, so if the target is different from the prior one, it must not assert DEVSEL# until the third cycle (medium DEVSEL speed).
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] One case where this problem cannot arise is if the initiator knows somehow (presumably because the addresses share sufficient high-order bits) that the second transfer is addressed to the same target as the prior one.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] In that case, it may perform back-to-back transactions.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] It is also possible for the target to keep track of the requirements.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] If it never does fast DEVSEL, they are met trivially.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Targets that have this ability indicate it by a special bit in a PCI configuration register, and if all targets on a bus have it, all initiators may use back-to-back transfers freely.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] A subtractive decoding bus bridge must know to expect this extra delay in the event of back-to-back cycles, to advertise back-to-back support.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Starting from revision 2.1, the PCI specification includes optional 64-bit support.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] This is provided via an extended connector which provides the 64-bit bus extensions AD[63:32], C/BE[7:4]#, and PAR64, and a number of additional power and ground pins.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The 64-bit PCI connector can be distinguished from a 32-bit connector by the additional 64-bit segment.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Memory transactions between 64-bit devices may use all 64 bits to double the data transfer rate.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Non-memory transactions (including configuration and I/O space accesses) may not use the 64-bit extension.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] During a 64-bit burst, burst addressing works just as in a 32-bit transfer, but the address is incremented twice per data phase.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The starting address must be 64-bit aligned; i.e.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The data corresponding to the intervening addresses (with AD2 = 1) is carried on the upper half of the AD bus.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] To initiate a 64-bit transaction, the initiator drives the starting address on the AD bus and asserts REQ64# at the same time as FRAME#.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] If the selected target can support a 64-bit transfer for this transaction, it replies by asserting ACK64# at the same time as DEVSEL#.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] A target may decide on a per-transaction basis whether to allow a 64-bit transfer.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] If REQ64# is asserted during the address phase, the initiator also drives the high 32 bits of the address and a copy of the bus command on the high half of the bus.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] If the address requires 64 bits, a dual address cycle is still required, but the high half of the bus carries the upper half of the address and the final command code during both address phase cycles; this allows a 64-bit target to see the entire address and begin responding earlier.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] If the initiator sees DEVSEL# asserted without ACK64#, it performs 32-bit data phases.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The data which would have been transferred on the upper half of the bus during the first data phase is instead transferred during the second data phase.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Typically, the initiator drives all 64 bits of data before seeing DEVSEL#.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] If ACK64# is missing, it may cease driving the upper half of the data bus.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The REQ64# and ACK64# lines are held asserted for the entire transaction save the last data phase and deasserted at the same time as FRAME# and DEVSEL#, respectively.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The PAR64 line operates just like the PAR line, but provides even parity over AD[63:32] and C/BE[7:4]#.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] It is only valid for address phases if REQ64# is asserted.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] PAR64 is only valid for data phases if both REQ64# and ACK64# are asserted.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] PCI originally included optional support for write-back cache coherence.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] This required support by cacheable memory targets, which would listen to two pins from the cache on the bus, SDONE (snoop done) and SBO# (snoop backoff).
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Because this was rarely implemented in practice, it was deleted from revision 2.2 of the PCI specification, and the pins re-used for SMBus access in revision 2.3.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] The cache would watch all memory accesses, without asserting DEVSEL#.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] If it noticed an access that might be cached, it would drive SDONE low (snoop not done).
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] A coherence-supporting target would avoid completing a data phase (asserting TRDY#) until it observed SDONE high.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] In the case of a write to data that was clean in the cache, the cache would only have to invalidate its copy and would assert SDONE as soon as this was established.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] However, if the cache contained dirty data, the cache would have to write it back before the access could proceed. so it would assert SBO# when raising SDONE.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] This would signal the active target to assert STOP# rather than TRDY#, causing the initiator to disconnect and retry the operation later.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] In the meantime, the cache would arbitrate for the bus and write its data back to memory.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Targets supporting cache coherency are also required to terminate bursts before they cross cache lines.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] When developing and/or troubleshooting the PCI bus, examination of hardware signals can be very important.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Logic analyzers and bus analyzers are tools that collect, analyze, and decode signals for users to view in useful ways.
[src:pcie-interface/conventional-pci-p02] Companies such as Synopsys, Lattice Semiconductor and Rambus offer silicon IP cores to design semiconductor ASICs that use the PCI bus standard.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] Message signaled interrupts are supported in PCI bus since its version 2.2, and in later available PCI Express bus.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] Some non-PCI architectures also use message signaled interrupts.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] Traditionally, a device has an interrupt line (pin) which it asserts when it wants to signal an interrupt to the host processing environment.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] This traditional form of interrupt signalling is an out-of-band form of control signalling since it uses a dedicated path to send such control information, separately from the main data path.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] MSI replaces those dedicated interrupt lines with in-band signalling, by exchanging special messages that indicate interrupts through the main data path.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] In particular, MSI allows the device to write a small amount of interrupt-describing data to a special memory-mapped I/O address, and the chipset then delivers the corresponding interrupt to a processor.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] A common misconception with MSI is that it allows the device to send data to a processor as part of the interrupt.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] The data that is sent as part of the memory write transaction is used by the chipset to determine which interrupt to trigger on which processor; that data is not available for the device to communicate additional information to the interrupt handler.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] As an example, PCI Express does not have separate interrupt pins at all; instead, it uses special in-band messages to allow pin assertion or deassertion to be emulated.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] Some non-PCI architectures also use MSI; as another example, HP GSC devices do not have interrupt pins and can generate interrupts only by writing directly to the processor's interrupt register in memory space.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] The HyperTransport protocol also supports MSI.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] While more complex to implement in a device, message signalled interrupts have some significant advantages over pin-based out-of-band interrupt signalling.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] On the mechanical side, fewer pins makes for a simpler, cheaper, and more reliable connector.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] While this is no advantage to the standard PCI connector, PCI Express takes advantage of these savings.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] MSI increases the number of interrupts that are possible.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] While conventional PCI was limited to four interrupts per card (and, because they were shared among all cards, most are using only one), message signalled interrupts allow dozens of interrupts per card, when that is useful.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] There is also a slight performance advantage.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] In software, a pin-based interrupt could race with a posted write to memory.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] That is, the PCI device would write data to memory and then send an interrupt to indicate the DMA write was complete.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] However, a PCI bridge or memory controller might buffer the write in order to not interfere with some other memory use.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] The interrupt could arrive before the DMA write was complete, and the processor could read stale data from memory.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] To prevent this race, interrupt handlers were required to read from the device to ensure that the DMA write had finished.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] This read had a moderate performance penalty.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] An MSI write cannot pass a DMA write, so the race is eliminated.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] PCI defines two optional extensions to support Message Signalled Interrupts, MSI and MSI-X.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] PCI Express defines its own message-based mechanism to emulate legacy PCI interrupts.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] MSI (first defined in PCI 2.2) permits a device to allocate 1, 2, 4, 8, 16 or 32 interrupts.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] The device is programmed with an address to write to (this address is generally a control register in an interrupt controller), and a 16-bit data word to identify it.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] The interrupt number is added to the data word to identify the interrupt.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] Some platforms such as Windows do not use all 32 interrupts but only use up to 16 interrupts.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] MSI-X (first defined in PCI 3.0) permits a device to allocate up to 2048 interrupts.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] The single address used by original MSI was found to be restrictive for some architectures.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] In particular, it made it difficult to target individual interrupts to different processors, which is helpful in some high-speed networking applications.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] MSI-X allows a larger number of interrupts and gives each one a separate target address and data word.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] Devices with MSI-X do not necessarily support 2048 interrupts.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] Optional features in MSI (64-bit addressing and interrupt masking) are also mandatory with MSI-X.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] PCI Express does not have physical interrupt pins, but emulates the 4 physical interrupt pins of PCI via dedicated PCI Express Messages such as *Assert_INTA* and *Deassert_INTC*.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] PCI Express permits devices to use these legacy interrupt messages, retaining software compatibility with PCI drivers, but they are required to also support MSI or MSI-X in the PCI layer.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] On Intel systems, the LAPIC must be enabled for the PCI (and PCI Express) MSI/MSI-X to work, even on uniprocessor (single core) systems.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] In these systems, MSIs are handled by writing the interrupt vector directly into the LAPIC of the processor/core that needs to service the interrupt.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] The Intel LAPICs of 2009 supported up to 224 MSI-based interrupts.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] According to a 2009 Intel benchmark using Linux, using MSI reduced the latency of interrupts by a factor of almost three when compared to I/O APIC delivery.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] In the Microsoft family of operating systems, Windows Vista and later versions have support for both MSI and MSI-X.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] Support was added in the Longhorn development cycle around 2004.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] MSI is not supported in earlier versions like Windows XP or Windows Server 2003.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] Solaris Express 6/05 released in 2005 added support for MSI an MSI-X as part of their new device driver interface (DDI) interrupt framework.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] FreeBSD 6.3 and 7.0 released in 2008 added support for MSI and MSI-X.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] OpenBSD 5.0 released in 2011 added support for MSI.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] Linux gained support for MSI and MSI-X around 2003.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] Linux kernel versions before 2.6.20 are known to have serious bugs and limitations in their implementation of MSI/MSI-X.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] Haiku gained support for MSI around 2010.
[src:pcie-interface/message-signaled-interrupts] NetBSD 8.0 released in 2018 added support for MSI and MSI-X.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Compared to earlier standards, PCIe supports faster data transfer, uses fewer pins, takes up less space, and allows devices to be added or removed while the computer is running (hot swapping).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] It also includes better error detection and supports newer features like I/O virtualization for advanced computing needs.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] PCIe connections are made through *lanes*, which are pairs of conductors that send and receive data.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Devices can use one or more lanes depending on how much data they need to transfer.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] PCIe technology is also used in laptop expansion cards (like ExpressCard) and in storage connectors such as M.2, U.2, and SATA Express.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Conceptually, the PCI Express bus is a high-speed serial replacement of the older PCI/PCI-X bus.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] One of the key differences between the PCI Express bus and the older PCI is the bus topology; PCI uses a shared parallel bus architecture, in which the PCI host and all devices share a common set of address, data, and control lines.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] In contrast, PCI Express is based on point-to-point topology, with separate serial links connecting every device to the root complex (host).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Because of its shared bus topology, access to the older PCI bus is arbitrated (in the case of multiple masters), and limited to one master at a time, in a single direction.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Furthermore, the older PCI clocking scheme limits the bus clock to the slowest peripheral on the bus (regardless of the devices involved in the bus transaction).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] In contrast, a PCI Express bus link supports full-duplex communication between any two endpoints, with no inherent limitation on concurrent access across multiple endpoints.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] In terms of bus protocol, PCI Express communication is encapsulated in packets.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The work of packetizing and de-packetizing data and status-message traffic is handled by the transaction layer of the PCI Express port (described later).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Radical differences in electrical signaling and bus protocol require the use of a different mechanical form factor and expansion connectors (and thus, new motherboards and new adapter boards); PCI slots and PCI Express slots are not interchangeable.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] At the software level, PCI Express preserves backward compatibility with PCI; legacy PCI system software can detect and configure newer PCI Express devices without explicit support for the PCI Express standard, though new PCI Express features are inaccessible.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The PCI Express link between two devices can vary in size from one to 16 lanes.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] In a multi-lane link, the packet data is striped across lanes, and peak data throughput scales with the overall link width.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The lane count is automatically negotiated during device initialization and can be restricted by either endpoint.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] For example, a single-lane PCI Express (×1) card can be inserted into a multi-lane slot (×4, ×8, etc.), and the initialization cycle auto-negotiates the highest mutually supported lane count.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The link can dynamically down-configure itself to use fewer lanes, providing a failure tolerance in case bad or unreliable lanes are present.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The PCI Express standard defines link widths of ×1, ×2, ×4, ×8, and ×16.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Up to and including PCIe 5.0, ×12, and ×32 links were defined as well but virtually never used.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] This allows the PCI Express bus to serve both cost-sensitive applications where high throughput is not needed, and performance-critical applications such as 3D graphics, networking (10 Gigabit Ethernet or multiport Gigabit Ethernet), and enterprise storage (SAS or Fibre Channel).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Slots and connectors are only defined for a subset of these widths, with link widths in between using the next larger physical slot size.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] As a point of reference, a PCI-X (133 MHz 64-bit) device and a PCI Express 1.0 device using four lanes (×4) have roughly the same peak single-direction transfer rate of 1064 MB/s.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The PCI Express bus has the potential to perform better than the PCI-X bus in cases where multiple devices are transferring data simultaneously, or if communication with the PCI Express peripheral is bidirectional.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] PCI Express devices communicate via a logical connection called an *interconnect* or *link*.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] A link is a point-to-point communication channel between two PCI Express ports allowing both of them to send and receive ordinary PCI requests (configuration, I/O or memory read/write) and interrupts (INTx, MSI or MSI-X).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] At the physical level, a link is composed of one or more *lanes*.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Low-speed peripherals (such as an 802.11 Wi-Fi card) use a single-lane (×1) link, while a graphics adapter typically uses a much wider and therefore faster 16-lane (×16) link.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] A lane is composed of two differential signaling pairs, with one pair for receiving data and the other for transmitting.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Thus, each lane is composed of four wires or signal traces.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Conceptually, each lane is used as a full-duplex byte stream, transporting data packets in eight-bit "byte" format simultaneously in both directions between endpoints of a link.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Physical PCI Express links may contain 1, 4, 8 or 16 lanes.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Lane counts are written with an "x" prefix (for example, "×8" represents an eight-lane card or slot), with ×16 being the largest size in common use.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The bonded serial bus architecture was chosen over the traditional parallel bus because of the inherent limitations of the latter, including half-duplex operation, excess signal count, and inherently lower bandwidth due to timing skew.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Timing skew results from separate electrical signals within a parallel interface traveling through conductors of different lengths, on potentially different printed circuit board (PCB) layers, and at possibly different signal velocities.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Despite being transmitted simultaneously as a single word, signals on a parallel interface have different travel duration and arrive at their destinations at different times.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] When the interface clock period is shorter than the largest time difference between signal arrivals, recovery of the transmitted word is no longer possible.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Since timing skew over a parallel bus can amount to a few nanoseconds, the resulting bandwidth limitation is in the range of hundreds of megahertz.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] A serial interface does not exhibit timing skew because there is only one differential signal in each direction within each lane, and there is no external clock signal since clocking information is embedded within the serial signal itself.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] As such, typical bandwidth limitations on serial signals are in the multi-gigahertz range.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] PCI Express is one example of the general trend toward replacing parallel buses with serial interconnects; other examples include Serial ATA (SATA), USB, Serial Attached SCSI (SAS), FireWire (IEEE 1394), and RapidIO.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] In digital video, examples in common use are DVI, HDMI, and DisplayPort, but they were replacements for analog VGA, not for a parallel bus.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Multichannel serial design increases flexibility with its ability to allocate fewer lanes for slower devices.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] A **PCIe switch** is like a network switch, except that it works with PCIe connections.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] In the tree topology is one *upstream* port where it connects to a higher-level device (another switch or directly a PCIe bus) and a number of *downstream* ports.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The switch is responsible for receiving a packet from one port and forwarding it to an appropriate, different port.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] By doing packet-switching, the bandwidth is effectively shared across multiple downstream ports (compared to static lane bifurcation).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] A more advanced multi-host topology contains multiple upstream ports.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] A PCI Express add-in card fits into a slot of its physical size or larger (with ×16 as the largest used), but may not fit into a smaller PCI Express slot; for example, a ×16 card may not fit into a ×4 or ×8 slot.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Some slots use open-ended sockets to permit physically longer cards and negotiate the best available electrical and logical connection.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The number of lanes actually connected to a slot may also be fewer than the number supported by the physical slot size.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] An example is a ×16 slot that runs at ×4, which accepts any ×1, ×2, ×4, ×8 or ×16 card, but provides only four lanes.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Its specification may read as "×16 (×4 mode)" or "×16 (×4 signal)", while "mechanical @ electrical" notation (e.g.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The advantage is that such slots can accommodate a larger range of PCI Express cards without requiring motherboard hardware to support the full transfer rate.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Standard mechanical sizes are ×1, ×4, ×8, and ×16.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Cards using a number of lanes other than the standard mechanical sizes need to physically fit the next larger mechanical size (e.g. an ×2 card uses the ×4 size, or an ×12 card uses the ×16 size).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The cards themselves are designed and manufactured in various sizes.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] For example, solid-state drives (SSDs) that come in the form of PCI Express cards often use HHHL (half height, half length) and FHHL (full height, half length) to describe the physical dimensions of the card.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The concept of "full" and "half" heights and lengths are inherited from Conventional PCI.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The length levels beside full are not a PCIe standard, but only a manufacturer agreement.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Half length provides sufficient space for a ×16 connector.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Below that narrower data connectors need to be used.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] These dimensions can be freely mixed and matched, but larger dimensions tend to co-occur.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] There is a fixed distance of 57.15 millimetres (2.250 in) between the connector's key notch (middle ridge diving data and power) and the end of the card, which may be covered by an end plate with a screw-hole for installing onto the computer case.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] This fixed length ensures that cards do not protrude out of the chassis.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The slot spacing is exactly 0.8 inches (20 mm) on ATX motherboards.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] For further specifications of the slot, see #Physical layer below.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] 2012) gaming video cards usually exceed the height as well as thickness specified in the PCI Express standard, due to the need for more capable and quieter cooling fans, as gaming video cards often emit hundreds of watts of heat.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Modern computer cases are often wider to accommodate these taller cards, but not always.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Since full-length cards (312 mm) are uncommon, modern cases sometimes cannot accommodate them.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The thickness of these cards also typically occupies the space of 2 to 5 PCIe slots.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] In fact, even the methodology of how to measure the cards varies between vendors, with some including the metal bracket size in dimensions and others not.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] For instance, comparing three high-end video cards released in 2020: a Sapphire Radeon RX 5700 XT card measures 135 mm in height (excluding the metal bracket), which exceeds the PCIe standard height by 28 mm, another Radeon RX 5700 XT card by XFX measures 55 mm thick (i.e.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] 2.7 PCI slots at 20.32 mm), taking up 3 PCIe slots, while an Asus GeForce RTX 3080 video card takes up two slots and measures 140.1 mm × 318.5 mm × 57.8 mm, exceeding PCI Express's maximum height, length, and thickness respectively.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The following table identifies the conductors on each side of the edge connector on a PCI Express card.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The solder side of the printed circuit board (PCB) is the A-side, and the component side is the B-side.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] PRSNT1# and PRSNT2# pins must be slightly shorter than the rest, to ensure that a hot-plugged card is fully inserted.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The WAKE# pin uses full voltage to wake the computer, but must be pulled high from the standby power to indicate that the card is wake capable.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] All PCI express cards may consume up to 3 A at +3.3 V (9.9 W).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Some cards use two 8-pin connectors, allowing 375 W total (1 @ 75 W + 2 @ 150 W).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] This was newly standardized in PCI Express 4.0 CEM of 2018, though it was already in use before then.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The 8-pin PCI Express connector should not be confused with the EPS12V connector, which is mainly used for powering SMP and multi-core systems.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The power connectors are variants of the Molex Mini-Fit Jr. series connectors.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The 16-pin 12VHPWR connector is a standard for connecting graphics processing units (GPUs) to computer power supplies for up to 600 W power delivery.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] It was introduced by Nvidia in 2022 to supersede the previous 6- and 8-pin power connectors for GPUs.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The stated aim was to cater to the increasing power requirements of Nvidia GPUs.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The connector was formally adopted as part of PCI Express 5.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The connector was replaced by a minor revision called 12V-2x6, introduced in 2023 with PCIe CEM 5.1 and PCIe ECN 6.0, which changed the GPU- and PSU-side sockets to ensure that the sense pins only make contact if the power pins are seated properly.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The cables and their plugs remained unchanged.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The change is intended to prevent melting due to partial contact, but melting continued to be reported for GPUs with this new socket.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] There is a significant change in power negotiation with a new sense pin added.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] 12VHPWR connectors are marked with an "H+" symbol, whereas 12V-2x6 connectors are marked with an "H++" symbol.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] In 2021, PCIe Card Electromechanical (CEM, pronounced like "chem" in "chemistry") Specification introduced a connector for 48 Volts with two current-carrying contacts and four sense pins.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] It was retained into PCIe-CEM 5.1 of 2023.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The contacts are rated for 15 Amps continuous current.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The 48VHPWR connector can carry 720 watts.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Later it was removed and an incompatible 48V 1×2 connector was introduced where Sense0 and Sense1 are located farthest from each other.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Power excursion refers to short peaks of power draw exceeding the rated maximum (sustained) power level.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Since an add-on Engineering Change Notice (ECN) to PCIe-CEM 5.0, the additional power connectors need to be able to handle 100-microsecond power draw at 3× of maximum sustained power, reducing to 1× at the 1-second window level following a logarithmic line.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Since PCIe-ECM 5.1, slot power has a similar excursion expansion at 2.5× over 100 μs.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] In CEM 5.1, the added excursion limit is only provided after software configuration, specifically the Set_Slot_Power_Limit message.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The ECN is part of ATX 3.0 and PCIe CEM 5.1 is part of ATX 3.1.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Due to different dimensions, PCI Express Mini Cards are not physically compatible with standard full-size PCI Express slots; however, passive adapters exist that let them be used in full-size slots.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Dimensions of PCI Express Mini Cards are 30 mm × 50.95 mm (width × length) for a Full Mini Card.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] There is a 52-pin edge connector, consisting of two staggered rows on a 0.8 mm pitch.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Each row has eight contacts, a gap equivalent to four contacts, then a further 18 contacts.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Boards have a thickness of 1.0 mm, excluding the components.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] A "Half Mini Card" (sometimes abbreviated as HMC) is also specified, having approximately half the physical length of 26.8 mm.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] There are also half size mini PCIe cards that are 30 × 31.90 mm which is about half the length of a full size mini PCIe card.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Despite sharing the Mini PCI Express form factor, an mSATA slot is not necessarily electrically compatible with Mini PCI Express.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] For this reason, only certain notebooks are compatible with mSATA drives.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Most compatible systems are based on Intel's Sandy Bridge processor architecture, using the Huron River platform.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Notebooks such as Lenovo's ThinkPad T, W and X series, released in March–April 2011, have support for an mSATA SSD card in their WWAN card slot.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The ThinkPad Edge E220s/E420s, and the Lenovo IdeaPad Y460/Y560/Y570/Y580 also support mSATA.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On the contrary, the L-series among others can only support M.2 cards using the PCIe standard in the WWAN slot.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Some notebooks (notably the Asus Eee PC, the Apple MacBook Air, and the Dell mini9 and mini10) use a variant of the PCI Express Mini Card as an SSD.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] This variant uses the reserved and several non-reserved pins to implement SATA and IDE interface passthrough, keeping only USB, ground lines, and sometimes the core PCIe ×1 bus intact.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] This makes the "miniPCIe" flash and solid-state drives sold for netbooks largely incompatible with true PCI Express Mini implementations.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Also, the typical Asus miniPCIe SSD is 71 mm long, causing the Dell 51 mm model to often be (incorrectly) referred to as half length.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] A true 51 mm Mini PCIe SSD was announced in 2009, with two stacked PCB layers that allow for higher storage capacity.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The announced design preserves the PCIe interface, making it compatible with the standard mini PCIe slot.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] No working product has yet been developed.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Intel has numerous desktop boards with the PCIe ×1 Mini-Card slot that typically do not support mSATA SSD.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] A list of desktop boards that natively support mSATA in the PCIe ×1 Mini-Card slot (typically multiplexed with a SATA port) is provided on the Intel Support site.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] M.2 replaces the mSATA standard and Mini PCIe.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Computer bus interfaces provided through the M.2 connector are PCI Express 3.0 or higher (up to four lanes), Serial ATA 3.0, and USB 3.0 (a single logical port for each of the latter two).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] It is up to the manufacturer of the M.2 host or device to choose which interfaces to support, depending on the desired level of host support and device type.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Standard cables and connectors have been defined for ×1, ×4, ×8, and ×16 link widths, with a transfer rate of 250 MB/s per lane.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The PCI-SIG also expects the norm to evolve to reach 500 MB/s, as in PCI Express 2.0.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] An example of the uses of Cabled PCI Express is a metal enclosure, containing a number of PCIe slots and PCIe-to-ePCIe adapter circuitry.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] This device would not be possible had it not been for the ePCIe specification.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The most recent version of OCuLink, OCuLink-2, supports 8 GB/s or 16 GB/s (PCIe 4.0 ×4 or ×8) while the maximum bandwidth of a USB 80Gbit/s (USB4 Gen 4) or Thunderbolt 5 connection is 10 GB/s.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] OCulink is principally intended for PCIe (or SATA breakout) interconnections in servers, but also finds limited adoption on laptops for the connection of external GPU boxes.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] CopprLink uses SFF-TA-1032 connectors to support external PCIe cable for PCIe 5.0 x16 and PCIe 6.0 x16.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Numerous other form factors use, or are able to use, PCIe.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The PCIe slot connector can also carry protocols other than PCIe.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Some 9xx series Intel chipsets support Serial Digital Video Out, a proprietary technology that uses a slot to transmit video signals from the host CPU's integrated graphics instead of PCIe, using a supported add-in.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] While in early development, PCIe was initially referred to as *HSI* (for *High Speed Interconnect*), and underwent a name change to *3GIO* (for *3rd Generation I/O*) before finally settling on its PCI-SIG name *PCI Express*.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] A technical working group named the *Arapaho Work Group* (AWG) drew up the standard.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] For initial drafts, the AWG consisted only of Intel engineers; subsequently, the AWG expanded to include industry partners.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Since, PCIe has undergone several large and smaller revisions, improving on performance and other features.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Transfer rate refers to the encoded serial bit rate; 2.5 GT/s means 2.5 Gbit/s serial data rate.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Throughput indicates the usable bandwidth (i.e. only including the payload, not the 8b/10b, 128b/130b, or 242B/256B encoding overhead).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The PCIe 1.0 transfer rate of 2.5 GT/s per lane means a 2.5 Gbit/s serial bit rate; after applying a 8b/10b encoding, this corresponds to a useful throughput of 2.0 Gbit/s = 250 MB/s.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] In 2003, PCI-SIG introduced PCIe 1.0a, with a per-lane data rate of 0.25 gigabytes per second (GB/s) and a transfer rate of 2.5 gigatransfers per second (GT/s).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Transfer rate is expressed in transfers per second instead of bits per second because the number of transfers includes the overhead bits, which do not provide additional throughput; PCIe 1.x uses an 8b/10b encoding scheme, resulting in a 20% (= 2/10) overhead on the raw channel bandwidth.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] So in the PCIe terminology, transfer rate refers to the encoded bit rate: 2.5 GT/s is 2.5 Gbit/s on the encoded serial link.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] This corresponds to 2.0 Gbit/s of pre-coded data or 0.25 GB/s, which is referred to as throughput in PCIe.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] This updated specification includes clarifications and several improvements, but is fully compatible with PCI Express 1.0a.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] PCI-SIG announced the availability of the PCI Express Base 2.0 specification on 15 January 2007.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The PCIe 2.0 standard doubles the transfer rate compared with PCIe 1.0 to 5 GT/s and the per-lane throughput rises from 250 MB/s to 500 MB/s.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Consequently, a 16-lane PCIe connector (×16) can support an aggregate throughput of up to 8 GB/s.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] PCIe 2.0 motherboard slots are fully backward compatible with PCIe v1.x cards.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] PCIe 2.0 cards are also generally backward compatible with PCIe 1.x motherboards, using the available bandwidth of PCI Express 1.1.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Overall, graphic cards or motherboards designed for v2.0 work, with the other being v1.1 or v1.0a.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The PCI-SIG also said that PCIe 2.0 features improvements to the point-to-point data transfer protocol and its software architecture.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Intel's first PCIe 2.0 capable chipset was the X38 and boards began to ship from various vendors (Abit, Asus, Gigabyte) as of 21 October 2007.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] AMD started supporting PCIe 2.0 with its AMD 700 chipset series and nVidia started with the MCP72.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] All of Intel's prior chipsets, including the Intel P35 chipset, supported PCIe 1.1 or 1.0a.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Like 1.x, PCIe 2.0 uses an 8b/10b encoding scheme, therefore delivering, per-lane, an effective 4 Gbit/s max. transfer rate from its 5 GT/s raw data rate.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] PCI Express 2.1 (with its specification dated 4 March 2009) supports a large proportion of the management, support, and troubleshooting systems planned for full implementation in PCI Express 3.0.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] However, the speed is the same as PCI Express 2.0.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] PCI Express 3.0 Base specification revision 3.0 was made available in November 2010, after multiple delays.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] In August 2007, PCI-SIG announced that PCI Express 3.0 would carry a bit rate of 8 gigatransfers per second (GT/s), and that it would be backward compatible with existing PCI Express implementations.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] At that time, it was also announced that the final specification for PCI Express 3.0 would be delayed until Q2 2010.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] New features for the PCI Express 3.0 specification included a number of optimizations for enhanced signaling and data integrity, including transmitter and receiver equalization, PLL improvements, clock data recovery, and channel enhancements of currently supported topologies.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] PCI Express 3.0 upgraded the line encoding scheme to 128b/130b from the previous 8b/10b encoding, reducing the bandwidth overhead from 20% of PCI Express 2.0 to approximately 1.54% (= 2/130).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] PCI Express 3.0's 8 GT/s bit rate effectively delivers 985 MB/s per lane, nearly doubling the lane bandwidth relative to PCI Express 2.0.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On 18 November 2010, the PCI-SIG officially published the finalized PCI Express 3.0 specification to its members to build devices based on this new version of PCI Express.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] In September 2013, PCI Express 3.1 specification was announced for release in late 2013 or early 2014, consolidating various improvements to the published PCI Express 3.0 specification in three areas: power management, performance and functionality.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] PCI Express 4.0 specs also bring OCuLink-2, an alternative to Thunderbolt.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] OCuLink version 2 has up to 16 GT/s (16 GB/s total for ×8 lanes), while the maximum bandwidth of a Thunderbolt 3 link is 5 GB/s.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] At the 2016 PCI-SIG Developers Conference, Cadence, PLDA, and Synopsys demonstrated their development of PCIe 4.0 physical layer, controller, switch, and other IP blocks.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Mellanox Technologies announced the first 100 Gbit/s network adapter with PCIe 4.0 on 15 June 2016, and the first 200 Gbit/s network adapter with PCIe 4.0 on 10 November 2016.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] In August 2016, Synopsys presented a test setup with FPGA clocking a lane to PCIe 4.0 speeds at the Intel Developer Forum.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Their IP has been licensed to several firms planning to present their chips and products at the end of 2016.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On the IEEE Hot Chips Symposium in August 2016 IBM announced the first CPU with PCIe 4.0 support, POWER9.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] PCI-SIG officially announced the release of the final PCI Express 4.0 specification on 8 June 2017.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The spec includes improvements in flexibility, scalability, and lower-power.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On 5 December 2017 IBM announced the first system with PCIe 4.0 slots, Power AC922.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] AMD announced on 9 January 2019 its upcoming Zen 2-based processors and X570 chipset would support PCIe 4.0.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] AMD had hoped to enable partial support for older chipsets, but instability caused by motherboard traces not conforming to PCIe 4.0 specifications made that impossible.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Intel released their first mobile CPUs with PCI Express 4.0 support in mid-2020, as a part of the Tiger Lake microarchitecture.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] In June 2017, PCI-SIG announced the PCI Express 5.0 preliminary specification.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Bandwidth was expected to increase to 32 GT/s, yielding 63 GB/s in each direction in a 16-lane configuration.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The draft spec was expected to be standardized in 2019.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Initially, 25.0 GT/s was also considered for technical feasibility.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On 7 June 2017 at PCI-SIG DevCon, Synopsys recorded the first demonstration of PCI Express 5.0 at 32 GT/s.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On 31 May 2018, PLDA announced the availability of their XpressRICH5 PCIe 5.0 Controller IP based on draft 0.7 of the PCIe 5.0 specification on the same day.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On 10 December 2018, the PCI SIG released version 0.9 of the PCIe 5.0 specification to its members, and on 17 January 2019, PCI SIG announced the version 0.9 had been ratified, with version 1.0 targeted for release in the first quarter of 2019.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On 29 May 2019, PCI-SIG officially announced the release of the final PCI Express 5.0 specification.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The PCI Express 5.0 retained backward compatibility with previous versions of PCI Express specifications.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On 20 November 2019, Jiangsu Huacun presented the first PCIe 5.0 Controller HC9001 in a 12 nm manufacturing process and production started in 2020.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On 17 August 2020, IBM announced the Power10 processor with PCIe 5.0 and up to 32 lanes per single-chip module (SCM) and up to 64 lanes per double-chip module (DCM).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On 9 September 2021, IBM announced the Power E1080 Enterprise server with planned availability date 17 September.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] It can have up to 16 Power10 SCMs with maximum of 32 slots per system which can act as PCIe 5.0 ×8 or PCIe 4.0 ×16.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Alternatively they can be used as PCIe 5.0 ×16 slots for optional optical CXP converter adapters connecting to external PCIe expansion drawers.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On 27 October 2021, Intel announced the 12th Gen Intel Core CPU family, the world's first consumer x86-64 processors with PCIe 5.0 (up to 16 lanes) connectivity.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On 22 March 2022, Nvidia announced Nvidia Hopper GH100 GPU, the world's first PCIe 5.0 GPU.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On 23 May 2022, AMD announced its Zen 4 architecture with support for up to 24 lanes of PCIe 5.0 connectivity on consumer platforms and 128 lanes on server platforms.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On 18 June 2019, PCI-SIG announced the development of PCI Express 6.0 specification.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Bandwidth is expected to increase to 64 GT/s, yielding 128 GB/s in each direction in a 16-lane configuration, with a target release date of 2021.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The new standard uses 4-level pulse-amplitude modulation (PAM-4) with a low-latency forward error correction (FEC) in place of non-return-to-zero (NRZ) modulation.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Unlike previous PCI Express versions, forward error correction is used to increase data integrity and PAM-4 is used as line code so that two bits are transferred per transfer.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] With 64 GT/s data transfer rate (raw bit rate), up to 121 GB/s in each direction is possible in ×16 configuration.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On 24 February 2020, the PCI Express 6.0 revision 0.5 specification (a "first draft" with all architectural aspects and requirements defined) was released.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On 5 November 2020, the PCI Express 6.0 revision 0.7 specification (a "complete draft" with electrical specifications validated via test chips) was released.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On 6 October 2021, the PCI Express 6.0 revision 0.9 specification (a "final draft") was released.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On 11 January 2022, PCI-SIG officially announced the release of the final PCI Express 6.0 specification.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The PCI Express 6.0 retained backward compatibility with previous versions of PCI Express specifications.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] PAM-4 coding results in a vastly higher bit error rate (BER) of 10−6 (vs.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] 10−12 previously), so in place of 128b/130b encoding, a 3-way interlaced forward error correction (FEC) is used in addition to cyclic redundancy check (CRC).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] A fixed 256 byte Flow Control Unit (FLIT) block carries 242 bytes of data, which includes variable-sized transaction level packets (TLP) and data link layer payload (DLLP); remaining 14 bytes are reserved for 8-byte CRC and 6-byte FEC.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] 3-way Gray code is used in PAM-4/FLIT mode to reduce error rate; the interface does not switch to NRZ and 128/130b encoding even when retraining to lower data rates.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] PCIe 6.0 hardware was not launched until August 2025, roughly three years after the release of the final specifications and shortly after the publication of the PCIe 7.0 specifications.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The delay was described as unprecedented, with *PCWorld* noting that for many years PCIe 6.0 existed "solely on paper".
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On 21 June 2022, PCI-SIG announced the development of PCI Express 7.0 specification.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] It will deliver 128 GT/s raw bit rate and up to 242 GB/s per direction in ×16 configuration, using the same PAM4 signaling as version 6.0.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Doubling of the data rate will be achieved by fine-tuning channel parameters to decrease signal losses and improve power efficiency, but signal integrity is expected to be a challenge.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The specification is expected to be finalized in 2025.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On 3 April 2024, the PCI Express 7.0 revision 0.5 specification (a "first draft") was released.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On 17 January 2025, PCI-SIG announced the release of PCIe 7.0 specification version 0.7 (a "complete draft").
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On 19 March 2025, PCI-SIG announced the release of PCIe 7.0 specification version 0.9 (a "final draft"); planned final release is still in 2025.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On 11 June 2025, PCI-SIG officially announced the release of the final PCI Express 7.0 specification.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] At its release, PCI-SIG commented that it did not see the PCIe 7.0 coming to the PC market for some time.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Instead the interface is initially targeted at cloud computing, 800-gigabit Ethernet, and artificial intelligence applications.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] On 5 August 2025, PCI-SIG announced the development of PCI Express 8.0.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] The specification is planned for release by year 2028.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] It will deliver double the speed of the previous version, 256.0 GT/s raw bit rate and up to 1 TB/s bi-directionally via ×16 configuration.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] Historically, the earliest adopters of a new PCIe specification generally begin designing with the Draft 0.5 as they can confidently build up their application logic around the new bandwidth definition and often even start developing for any new protocol features.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p01] At the Draft 0.5 stage, however, there is still a strong likelihood of changes in the actual PCIe protocol layer implementation, so designers responsible for developing these blocks internally may be more hesitant to begin work than those using interface IP from external sources.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The PCIe link is built around dedicated unidirectional couples of serial (1-bit), point-to-point connections known as *lanes*.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] This is in sharp contrast to the earlier PCI connection, which is a bus-based system where all the devices share the same bidirectional, 32-bit or 64-bit parallel bus.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] PCI Express is a layered protocol, consisting of a *transaction layer*, a *data link layer*, and a *physical layer*.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The Data Link Layer is subdivided to include a media access control (MAC) sublayer.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The Physical Layer is subdivided into logical and electrical sublayers.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The Physical logical-sublayer contains a physical coding sublayer (PCS).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The terms are borrowed from the IEEE 802 networking protocol model.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The PCIe Physical Layer (*PHY*, *PCIEPHY*, *PCI Express PHY*, or *PCIe PHY*) specification is divided into two sub-layers, corresponding to electrical and logical specifications.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The logical sublayer is sometimes further divided into a MAC sublayer and a PCS, although this division is not formally part of the PCIe specification.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] A specification published by Intel, the PHY Interface for PCI Express (PIPE), defines the MAC/PCS functional partitioning and the interface between these two sub-layers.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The PIPE specification also identifies the *physical media attachment* (PMA) layer, which includes the SerDes (serializer/deserializer) and other analog circuitry; however, since SerDes implementations vary greatly among ASIC vendors, PIPE does not specify an interface between the PCS and PMA.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] At the electrical level, each lane consists of two unidirectional differential pairs operating at 2.5, 5, 8, 16 or 32 Gbit/s, depending on the negotiated capabilities.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Transmit and receive are separate differential pairs, for a total of four data wires per lane.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] A connection between any two PCIe devices is known as a *link*, and is built up from a collection of one or more *lanes*.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] All devices must minimally support single-lane (×1) link.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Devices may optionally support wider links composed of up to 32 lanes.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] In both cases, PCIe negotiates the highest mutually supported number of lanes.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Many graphics cards, motherboards and BIOS versions are verified to support ×1, ×4, ×8 and ×16 connectivity on the same connection.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The width of a PCIe connector is 8.8 mm, while the height is 11.25 mm, and the length is variable.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The fixed section of the connector is 11.65 mm in length and contains two rows of 11 pins each (22 pins total), while the length of the other section is variable depending on the number of lanes.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The pins are spaced at 1 mm intervals, and the thickness of the card going into the connector is 1.6 mm.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] PCIe sends all control messages, including interrupts, over the same links used for data.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The serial protocol can never be blocked, so latency is still comparable to conventional PCI, which has dedicated interrupt lines.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] When the problem of IRQ sharing of pin based interrupts is taken into account and the fact that message signaled interrupts (MSI) can bypass an I/O APIC and be delivered to the CPU directly, MSI performance ends up being substantially better.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Data transmitted on multiple-lane links is interleaved, meaning that each successive byte is sent down successive lanes.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The PCIe specification refers to this interleaving as *data striping*.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] While requiring significant hardware complexity to synchronize (or deskew) the incoming striped data, striping can significantly reduce the latency of the *n*th byte on a link.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] While the lanes are not tightly synchronized, there is a limit to the *lane to lane skew* of 20/8/6 ns for 2.5/5/8 GT/s so the hardware buffers can re-align the striped data.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Due to padding requirements, striping may not necessarily reduce the latency of small data packets on a link.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] As with other high data rate serial transmission protocols, the clock is embedded in the signal.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] At the physical level, PCI Express 2.0 utilizes the 8b/10b encoding scheme (line code) to ensure that strings of consecutive identical digits (zeros or ones) are limited in length.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] This coding was used to prevent the receiver from losing track of where the bit edges are.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] In this coding scheme every eight (uncoded) payload bits of data are replaced with 10 (encoded) bits of transmit data, causing a 20% overhead in the electrical bandwidth.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] To improve the available bandwidth, PCI Express version 3.0 instead uses 128b/130b encoding (1.54% overhead).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Line encoding limits the run length of identical-digit strings in data streams and ensures the receiver stays synchronised to the transmitter via clock recovery.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] A desirable balance (and therefore spectral density) of 0 and 1 bits in the data stream is achieved by XORing a known binary polynomial as a "scrambler" to the data stream in a feedback topology.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Because the scrambling polynomial is known, the data can be recovered by applying the XOR a second time.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Both the scrambling and descrambling steps are carried out in hardware.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Dual simplex in PCIe means there are two simplex channels on every PCIe lane.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Simplex means communication is only possible in one direction.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] By having two simplex channels, two-way communication is made possible.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] One differential pair is used for each channel.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] On the transmit side, the data link layer generates an incrementing sequence number for each outgoing TLP.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] It serves as a unique identification tag for each transmitted TLP, and is inserted into the header of the outgoing TLP.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] A 32-bit cyclic redundancy check code (known in this context as Link CRC or LCRC) is also appended to the end of each outgoing TLP.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] On the receive side, the received TLP's LCRC and sequence number are both validated in the link layer.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] If either the LCRC check fails (indicating a data error), or the sequence-number is out of range (non-consecutive from the last valid received TLP), then the bad TLP, as well as any TLPs received after the bad TLP, are considered invalid and discarded.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The receiver sends a negative acknowledgement message (NAK) with the sequence-number of the invalid TLP, requesting re-transmission of all TLPs forward of that sequence-number.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] If the received TLP passes the LCRC check and has the correct sequence number, it is treated as valid.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The link receiver increments the sequence-number (which tracks the last received good TLP), and forwards the valid TLP to the receiver's transaction layer.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] If the transmitter receives a NAK message, or no acknowledgement (NAK or ACK) is received until a timeout period expires, the transmitter must retransmit all TLPs that lack a positive acknowledgement (ACK).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Barring a persistent malfunction of the device or transmission medium, the link-layer presents a reliable connection to the transaction layer, since the transmission protocol ensures delivery of TLPs over an unreliable medium.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] In addition to sending and receiving TLPs generated by the transaction layer, the data-link layer also generates and consumes data link layer packets (DLLPs).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] ACK and NAK signals are communicated via DLLPs, as are some power management messages and flow control credit information (on behalf of the transaction layer).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] In practice, the number of in-flight, unacknowledged TLPs on the link is limited by two factors: the size of the transmitter's replay buffer (which must store a copy of all transmitted TLPs until the remote receiver ACKs them), and the flow control credits issued by the receiver to a transmitter.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] PCI Express requires all receivers to issue a minimum number of credits, to guarantee a link allows sending PCIConfig TLPs and message TLPs.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] PCI Express implements split transactions (transactions with request and response separated by time), allowing the link to carry other traffic while the target device gathers data for the response.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] PCI Express uses credit-based flow control.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] In this scheme, a device advertises an initial amount of credit for each received buffer in its transaction layer.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The device at the opposite end of the link, when sending transactions to this device, counts the number of credits each TLP consumes from its account.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The sending device may only transmit a TLP when doing so does not make its consumed credit count exceed its credit limit.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] When the receiving device finishes processing the TLP from its buffer, it signals a return of credits to the sending device, which increases the credit limit by the restored amount.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The credit counters are modular counters, and the comparison of consumed credits to credit limit requires modular arithmetic.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The advantage of this scheme (compared to other methods such as wait states or handshake-based transfer protocols) is that the latency of credit return does not affect performance, provided that the credit limit is not encountered.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] This assumption is generally met if each device is designed with adequate buffer sizes.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] PCIe 1.x is often quoted to support a data rate of 250 MB/s in each direction, per lane.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] This figure is a calculation from the physical signaling rate (2.5 gigabaud) divided by the encoding overhead (10 bits per byte).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] This means a sixteen lane (×16) PCIe card would then be theoretically capable of 16×250 MB/s = 4 GB/s in each direction.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] While this is correct in terms of data bytes, more meaningful calculations are based on the usable data payload rate, which depends on the profile of the traffic, which is a function of the high-level (software) application and intermediate protocol levels.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Like other high data rate serial interconnect systems, PCIe has a protocol and processing overhead due to the additional transfer robustness (CRC and acknowledgements).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Long continuous unidirectional transfers (such as those typical in high-performance storage controllers) can approach >95% of PCIe's raw (lane) data rate.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] These transfers also benefit the most from increased number of lanes (×2, ×4, etc.) But in more typical applications (such as a USB or Ethernet controller), the traffic profile is characterized as short data packets with frequent enforced acknowledgements.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] This type of traffic reduces the efficiency of the link, due to overhead from packet parsing and forced interrupts (either in the device's host interface or the PC's CPU).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Being a protocol for devices connected to the same printed circuit board, it does not require the same tolerance for transmission errors as a protocol for communication over longer distances, and thus, this loss of efficiency is not particular to PCIe.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] A PCIe 1.x lane for example offers a data rate on top of the physical layer of 250 MB/s (simplex).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] This is due to a 2.5 GT/s bit rate multiplied by the efficiency of the 8b/10b line code (see #Comparison table).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] This is not the payload bandwidth but the physical layer bandwidth – a PCIe lane has to carry additional information for full functionality.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The Gen2 overhead is then 20, 24, or 28 bytes per transaction.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The Gen3 overhead is then 22, 26 or 30 bytes per transaction.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The Packet Efficiency = ⁠Payload/Payload + Overhead⁠ for a 128 byte payload is 86%, and 98% for a 1024 byte payload.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] For small accesses like register settings (4 bytes), the efficiency drops as low as 16%.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] That said, most PCIe config registers reside in a DMA region mapped to the CPU's control registers and require no bus access.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The maximum payload size (MPS) is set on all devices based on smallest maximum on any device in the chain.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] If one device has an MPS of 128 bytes, *all* devices of the tree must set their MPS to 128 bytes.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] In this case the bus will have a maximum efficiency of 86% for writes.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] PCI Express operates in consumer, server, and industrial applications, as a motherboard-level interconnect (to link motherboard-mounted peripherals), a passive backplane interconnect and as an expansion card interface for add-in boards.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] In virtually all modern (as of 2012) PCs, from consumer laptops and desktops to enterprise servers, the PCIe bus serves as the primary motherboard-level interconnect, connecting the host system-processor with both integrated peripherals (surface-mounted ICs) and add-on peripherals (expansion cards).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] In some of these systems, the PCIe bus co-exists with one or more legacy PCI buses, for backward compatibility with the large body of legacy PCI peripherals.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] As of 2013, PCI Express has replaced AGP as the default interface for graphics cards on new systems.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Almost all models of graphics cards released since 2010 by AMD (ATI) and Nvidia use PCI Express.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] AMD, Nvidia, and Intel have released motherboard chipsets that support as many as four PCIe ×16 slots, allowing tri-GPU and quad-GPU card configurations.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Theoretically, external PCIe could give a notebook the graphics power of a desktop, by connecting a notebook with any PCIe desktop video card (enclosed in its own external housing, with a power supply and cooling); this is possible with an ExpressCard or Thunderbolt interface.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] An ExpressCard interface provides bit rates of 5 Gbit/s (0.5 GB/s throughput), whereas a Thunderbolt interface provides bit rates of up to 40 Gbit/s (5 GB/s throughput).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] In 2006, Nvidia developed the Quadro Plex external PCIe family of GPUs that can be used for advanced graphic applications for the professional market.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] These video cards require a PCI Express ×8 or ×16 slot for the host-side card, which connects to the Plex via a VHDCI carrying eight PCIe lanes.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] In 2008, AMD announced the ATI XGP technology, based on a proprietary cabling system that is compatible with PCIe ×8 signal transmissions.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] This connector is available on the Fujitsu Amilo and the Acer Ferrari One notebooks.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Fujitsu launched their AMILO GraphicBooster enclosure for XGP soon thereafter.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Around 2010 Acer launched the Dynavivid graphics dock for XGP.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] In 2010, external card hubs were introduced that can connect to a laptop or desktop through a PCI ExpressCard slot.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] These hubs can accept full-sized graphics cards.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Examples include MSI GUS, Village Instrument's ViDock, the Asus XG Station, Bplus PE4H V3.2 adapter, as well as more improvised DIY devices.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] However such solutions are limited by the size (often only ×1) and version of the available PCIe slot on a laptop.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The Intel Thunderbolt interface has provided a new option to connect with a PCIe card externally.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Magma has released the ExpressBox 3T, which can hold up to three PCIe cards (two at ×8 and one at ×4).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] MSI also released the Thunderbolt GUS II, a PCIe chassis dedicated for video cards.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Other products such as the Sonnet's Echo Express and mLogic's mLink are Thunderbolt PCIe chassis in a smaller form factor.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] In 2017, more fully featured external card hubs were introduced, such as the Razer Core, which has a full-length PCIe ×16 interface.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The PCI Express protocol can be used as data interface to flash memory devices, such as memory cards and solid-state drives (SSDs).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The XQD card is a memory card format utilizing PCI Express, developed by the CompactFlash Association, with transfer rates of up to 1 GB/s.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Many high-performance, enterprise-class SSDs are designed as PCI Express RAID controller cards.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Before NVMe was standardized, many of these cards utilized proprietary interfaces and custom drivers to communicate with the operating system; they had much higher transfer rates (over 1 GB/s) and IOPS (over one million I/O operations per second) when compared to Serial ATA or SAS drives.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] For example, in 2011 OCZ and Marvell co-developed a native PCI Express solid-state drive controller for a PCI Express 3.0 ×16 slot with maximum capacity of 12 TB and a performance of to 7.2 GB/s sequential transfers and up to 2.52 million IOPS in random transfers.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] SATA Express was an interface for connecting SSDs through SATA-compatible ports, optionally providing multiple PCI Express lanes as a pure PCI Express connection to the attached storage device.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] M.2 is a specification for internally mounted computer expansion cards and associated connectors, which can use up to four PCI Express lanes.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] PCI Express storage devices can implement both AHCI logical interface for backward compatibility, and NVM Express logical interface for much faster I/O operations provided by utilizing internal parallelism offered by such devices.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Enterprise-class SSDs can also implement SCSI over PCI Express.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Certain data-center applications (such as large computer clusters) require the use of fiber-optic interconnects due to the distance limitations inherent in copper cabling.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Typically, a network-oriented standard such as Ethernet or Fibre Channel suffices for these applications, but in some cases the overhead introduced by routable protocols is undesirable and a lower-level interconnect, such as InfiniBand, RapidIO, or NUMAlink is needed.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Local-bus standards such as PCIe and HyperTransport can in principle be used for this purpose, but as of 2015, solutions are only available from niche vendors such as Dolphin ICS, and TTTech Auto.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] PCIe 1.0 initially competed with PCI-X 2.0, with both specifications being ratified in 2003 and offering roughly the same maximum bandwidth (~4 GB/s).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] By 2005, however, PCIe emerged as the dominant technology.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Other communications standards based on high bandwidth serial architectures include InfiniBand, RapidIO, HyperTransport, Intel QuickPath Interconnect, the Mobile Industry Processor Interface (MIPI), and NVLink.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Differences are based on the trade-offs between flexibility and extensibility vs latency and overhead.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] For example, making the system hot-pluggable, as with Infiniband but not PCI Express, requires that software track network topology changes.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Another example is making the packets shorter to decrease latency (as is required if a bus must operate as a memory interface).
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Smaller packets mean packet headers consume a higher percentage of the packet, thus decreasing the effective bandwidth.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Examples of bus protocols designed for this purpose are RapidIO and HyperTransport.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] PCI Express falls somewhere in the middle, targeted by design as a system interconnect (local bus) rather than a device interconnect or routed network protocol.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Additionally, its design goal of software transparency constrains the protocol and raises its latency somewhat.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] Delays in PCIe 4.0 implementations led to the Gen-Z consortium, the CCIX effort and an open Coherent Accelerator Processor Interface (CAPI) all being announced by the end of 2016.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] On 11 March 2019, Intel presented Compute Express Link (CXL), a new interconnect bus, based on the PCI Express 5.0 physical layer infrastructure.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The initial promoters of the CXL specification included: Alibaba, Cisco, Dell EMC, Facebook, Google, HPE, Huawei, Intel and Microsoft.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The PCI-SIG Integrators List lists products made by PCI-SIG member companies that have passed compliance testing.
[src:pcie-interface/pci-express-p02] The list include switches, bridges, NICs, SSDs, etc.
[src:pcie-interface/root-complex] In a PCI Express (PCIe) system, a **root complex** device connects the CPU and memory subsystem to the PCI Express switch fabric composed of one or more PCIe or PCI devices.
[src:pcie-interface/root-complex] A root complex is sometimes referred to **PCI root bridge**.
[src:pcie-interface/root-complex] The root complex generates transaction requests on behalf of the CPU, which is interconnected through a local bus.
[src:pcie-interface/root-complex] Root complex functionality may be integrated in the chipset and/or the CPU.
[src:pcie-interface/root-complex] A root complex may contain more than one PCI Express port and multiple switch devices can be connected to ports on the root complex or cascaded.
[src:pcie-interface/root-complex] The PCIe Root Complex holds a master copy of a 'Type 1 Configuration Table' that defines the host memory space that is accessible from each Endpoint device.
[src:pcie-interface/root-complex] In addition, each PCIe Endpoint device holds a master copy of its own memory space map in the host system memory as a 'Type 0 Configuration Table', this configuration table in each device allows the host to access the local memory of a PCIe device.
[src:pcie-interface/root-complex] Both the Type 1 and Type 0 configuration tables are set up by the Host Operating System that controls the Root Complex by a process known as enumeration and which acts to build a device memory map for the system by querying each bridge, and endpoint device connected on the bus network.
[src:pcie-interface/root-complex] Similarly, a PCIe Bridge acts a tiered root complex with a "Type 0 Configuration Table".
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] A **Serializer/Deserializer** (**SerDes**) is a pair of functional blocks commonly used in high speed communications to compensate for limited input/output.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] These blocks convert data between serial data and parallel interfaces in each direction.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] The term "SerDes" generically refers to interfaces used in various technologies and applications.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] The primary use of a SerDes is to provide data transmission over a single line or a differential pair in order to minimize the number of I/O pins and interconnects.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] The basic SerDes function is made up of two functional blocks: the Parallel In Serial Out (PISO) block (a.k.a.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] Parallel-to-Serial converter) and the Serial In Parallel Out (SIPO) block (a.k.a.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] There are 4 different SerDes architectures: (1) Parallel clock SerDes, (2) Embedded clock SerDes, (3) 8b/10b SerDes, (4) Bit interleaved SerDes.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] The PISO (Parallel Input, Serial Output) block typically has a parallel clock input, a set of data input lines, and input data latches.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] It may use an internal or external phase-locked loop (PLL) to multiply the incoming parallel clock up to the serial frequency.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] The simplest form of the PISO has a single shift register that receives the parallel data once per parallel clock, and shifts it out at the higher serial clock rate.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] Implementations may also make use of a double-buffered register to avoid metastability when transferring data between clock domains.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] The SIPO (Serial Input, Parallel Output) block typically has a receive clock output, a set of data output lines and output data latches.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] The receive clock may have been recovered from the data by the serial clock recovery technique.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] However, SerDes which do not transmit a clock use reference clock to lock the PLL to the correct Tx frequency, avoiding low harmonic frequencies present in the data stream.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] The SIPO block then divides the incoming clock down to the parallel rate.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] Implementations typically have two registers connected as a double buffer.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] One register is used to clock in the serial stream, and the other is used to hold the data for the slower, parallel side.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] Some types of SerDes include encoding/decoding blocks.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] The purpose of this encoding/decoding is typically to place at least statistical bounds on the rate of signal transitions to allow for easier clock recovery in the receiver, to provide framing, and to provide DC balance.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] Parallel clock SerDes is normally used to serialize a parallel bus input along with data address & control signals.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] The serialized stream is sent along with a reference clock.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] The clock jitter tolerance at the serializer is 5–10 ps rms.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] An embedded clock SerDes serializes data and clock into a single stream.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] One cycle of clock signal is transmitted first, followed by the data bit stream; this creates a periodic rising edge at the start of the data bit stream.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] As the clock is explicitly embedded and can be recovered from the bit stream, the serializer (transmitter) clock jitter tolerance is relaxed to 80–120 ps rms, while the reference clock disparity at the deserializer can be ±50,000 ppm (i.e.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] 8b/10b SerDes maps each data byte to a 10-bit code before serializing the data.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] The deserializer uses the reference clock to monitor the recovered clock from the bit stream.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] As the clock information is synthesized into the data bit stream, rather than explicitly embedding it, the serializer (transmitter) clock jitter tolerance is to 5–10 ps rms and the reference clock disparity at the deserializer is ±100 ppm.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] A common coding scheme used with SerDes is 8b/10b encoding.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] This supports DC-balance, provides framing, and guarantees frequent transitions, allowing a receiver to extract the embedded clock.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] The control codes allow framing, typically on the start of a packet.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] The typical 8b/10b SerDes parallel side interfaces have one clock line, one control line and 8 data lines.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] Such serializer-plus-8b/10b encoder, and deserializer-plus-decoder blocks are defined in the Gigabit Ethernet specification.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] Another common coding scheme used with SerDes is 64b/66b encoding.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] This scheme statistically delivers DC-balance and transitions through the use of a scrambler.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] Framing is delivered through the deterministic transitions of the added framing bits.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] Such serializer-plus-64b/66b encoder and deserializer-plus-decoder blocks are defined in the 10 Gigabit Ethernet specification.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] The transmit side comprises a 64b/66b encoder, a scrambler, and a gearbox that converts the 66b signal to a 16-bit interface.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] Another serializer then converts this 16-bit interface into a fully serial signal.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] Bit interleaved SerDes multiplexes several slower serial data streams into faster serial streams, and the receiver demultiplexes the faster bitstreams back to slower streams.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] The Optical Internetworking Forum (OIF) has published the Common Electrical I/O (CEI) Interoperability Agreements (IAs), that have defined six generations of the electrical interface of SerDes, at 3.125, 6, 10, 28, 56 and 112 Gb/s.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] The OIF has announced new projects at 224 Gb/s.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] The OIF also published three earlier generations of electrical interfaces.
[src:pcie-interface/serdes] These IAs have been adopted or adapted or have influenced high speed electrical interfaces defined by IEEE 802.3, Infiniband, RapidIO, Fibre Channel and numerous others.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] In telecommunication and data transmission, **serial communication** is the process of sending data one bit at a time, sequentially, over a communication channel or computer bus.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] This is in contrast to parallel communication, where several bits are sent as a whole, on a link with several parallel channels.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] Serial communication is used for all long-haul communication and most computer networks, where the cost of cable and difficulty of synchronization make parallel communication impractical.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] The migration from PCI to PCI Express (PCIe) is an example.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] Modern high speed serial interfaces such as PCIe send data several bits at a time using modulation/encoding techniques such as PAM4 which groups 2 bits at a time into a single symbol, and several symbols are still sent one at a time.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] This replaces PAM2 or non return to zero (NRZ) which only sends one bit at a time, or in other words one bit per symbol.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] The symbols are sent at a speed known as the symbol rate or the baud rate.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] Many serial communication systems were originally designed to transfer data over relatively large distances through some sort of data cable.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] Practically all long-distance communication transmits data one bit at a time, rather than in parallel, because it reduces the cost of the cable.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] The cables that carry this data (other than "the" serial cable) and the computer ports they plug into are usually referred to with a more specific name, to reduce confusion.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] Keyboard and mouse cables and ports are almost invariably serial—such as PS/2 port, Apple Desktop Bus and USB.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] The cables that carry digital video are also mostly serial—such as coax cable plugged into a HD-SDI port, a webcam plugged into a USB port or FireWire port, Ethernet cable connecting an IP camera to a Power over Ethernet port, FPD-Link, digital telephone lines (ex.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] Other such cables and ports, transmitting data one bit at a time, include Serial ATA, Serial SCSI, Ethernet cable plugged into Ethernet ports, the Display Data Channel using previously reserved pins of the VGA connector or the DVI port or the HDMI port.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] Many communication systems were generally designed to connect two integrated circuits on the same printed circuit board, connected by signal traces on that board (rather than external cables).
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] Integrated circuits are more expensive when they have more pins.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] To reduce the number of pins in a package, many ICs use a serial bus to transfer data when speed is not important.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] Some examples of such low-cost lower-speed serial buses include RS-232, DALI, SPI, CAN bus, I²C, UNI/O, and 1-Wire.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] Higher-speed serial buses include USB, SATA and PCI Express.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] The communication links, across which computers (or parts of computers) talk to one another, may be either serial or parallel.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] A parallel link transmits several streams of data simultaneously along multiple channels (e.g., wires, printed circuit tracks, or optical fibers); whereas, a serial link transmits only a single stream of data.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] The rationale for parallel communication was the added benefit of having Direct Memory Access to the 8-bit or 16-bit registry addresses at a time when mapping direct data lanes was more convenient and faster than synchronizing data serially.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] Although a serial link may seem inferior to a parallel one, since it can transmit less data per clock cycle, it is often the case that serial links can be clocked considerably faster than parallel links in order to achieve a higher data rate.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] The transition from parallel to serial buses was allowed by Moore's law which allowed for the incorporation of SerDes in integrated circuits.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] An electrical serial link only requires a pair of wires, whereas a parallel link requires several.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] Thus serial links can save on costs (also known as the Bill of Materials).
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] Differential signalling uses length-matched wires or conductors and are used in high speed serial links.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] Length-matching is easier to perform on serial links as they require fewer conductors.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] In many cases, serial is cheaper to implement than parallel.
[src:pcie-interface/serial-communication] Many ICs have serial interfaces, as opposed to parallel ones, so that they have fewer pins and are therefore less expensive.
